This paper deals with traceroute measurements in complex networks, specifically the Internet. It discusses the feasibility and infeasibility of inferring network topology given traceroute data, without any probabilistic assumptions. This falls under the category of network measurements and analysis, which is a subfield of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also uses graph theory and combinatorics to analyze the inferred topologies, which could fall under data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also discusses the limitations of measuring certain properties of the network, which could fall under information theory (cs.IT) and cryptography and security (cs.CR).
